{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_jasmine_ver01/data/sn78000533/00340580345/1945110801/0340.xml":{"full_text":"ivy\nV*\nxsu.\nPAGE FOUR'\nUr\n4\n4\n.K\n\u25a0\u2019I\nisf-\n3\nW'\n*7'1tive.\nv\n4\n\u2022r\nPotter#\nPark, Calif.\nLiverpool, Ohio.\nVirginia.\nu\nOFFICIAL JOURNAL OF\nTHE NATIONAL BROTHERHOOD OF OPERATIVE POTTERS\nand---\nEAST LIVERPOOL TRADES A LABOR COUNCIL\nPablished every Thursday at East Liverpool, Ohio, by the N. B. of O.\nP., owning and operating the Best Trades Newspaper aad Job\nPrinting Plant in the State.\n\u25a0ntered at Poetoffiee, East Liverpool, Ohio, April 20, 1902, as second\nclass matter. Accepted for mailing at Special Rates of Postage\nprovided for in Section 1108, Act of October 18,' 1917, authorised\nAugust 20, 1918.\nGsBoral Office, N. B. of O. P. Bailding, W. 4th St., BELL PHONE 575\nHARRY L. GILL.__________________ ____ Editor and Business Manager\nOne Year to Any Part of the United States or Canada------------------82.00\nPrwidext\u2014James M. Duffy, P. O. Box 762, East Liverpool, Ohio.\nFirst Vico President\u2014E. L. Wheatley, Room 215, Broad Street National\nBank Building, Trenton, ,8, New Jersey.\nv Second Vice President\n\u2014Finnic Hull, 2704 Florence Ave., Huntington\nThird Vice President\u2014James Slaven, Cannons Mills, East UvorpooL\ni Ohio.\nFourth Vice President\u2014Charles Zimmer, 1045 Ohio Avenue. Trenton, 8,\nJersey.\nFifth Vico President\u2014George Newbon, 847 Melrose Avenue, Trenton, 9,\nNew Jersey.\nSixth Vice President\u2014George Turner, 215 W. Fourth Street, East\nSeventh Vice President\u2014T. J. Desmond, 625 E. Lincoln Way, Minerva,\nOhio.\nV Eighth Vice President\u2014Joshua Chadwick, Grant Street, Nowell, West\nSecretary-Treasurer\u2014Chas. F. Jordan, P. O. Box 752, East Liverpool,\nOhio.___________________________________________\nGENERAL WARE STANDING COMMITTEE\nManufacturors-------------------- M. J. LYNCH. W. A. BETZ. J. T. HALL\nOperatives, CHAS. F. JORDAN. FREDERICK GLYNN, HARRY\nPODEWELS___________________________\nCHINA WARE STANDING COMMITTEE\nManufacturers.... E. K. KOOS. H. M. WALKER, W. A. BETZ\nOperatives. BERT CLARK, DAVID BEVAN, CHARLES JORDAN\nDECORATING STANDING COMMITTEE\nManufacturers, ROBERT DIETZ, Sr\u201e MARGARET PARKER, RAY\nBROOKES, W. A. BETZ\nOperatives, JAMES SLAVEN, THO8. WOOD, ROLAND HORTON\nISSUE OF AMERICAN DEMOCRACY\nTWICE the federal anti-poll tax bill has passed\nthe House, only to be filibustered to death in\nthe Senate, despite a strong majority in favor of\npassing the bill.\nFor the third time the bill is before the Sen\nate. The House passed it almost 3 to 1. The Senate\nCommittee on the Judiciary has recommended its\npassage to the Senate. But a little clique of irre\ncounciliables has announced they will talk the bill\nto death. again.\nMore than half the members of the' Senate\nhave definitely said they will vote for HR 7, the\nfederal anti-poll tax bill. They should have a\nchance to vote.\nBut the presiding officer must enforce every\nrule on the books\u2014and in this Congress, with no\nVice-President, the President Pro Tempore is Sen\nator McKellar of poll tax Tennessee. The Senators\nwho want a chance to vote must be alert to viola\ntions of the rules, and must insist the presiding\nofficer enforce the Senate\u2019s own rules.\nTwo-thirds of the Senators, regardless of\ntheir views on the bills, must be prepared to make\ndemocracy work by voting, .to: close debate.\nThe poll tax is not a wial issue it is an issue\nof American democracy. By the same token, in\nvoking cloture is not an issue of personal privilege\nit, too, is an issue of American democracy.\nUNSOUND ECONOMIC CONDITION\nTVHEN labor and the fanner fail to receive an\nadequate share of the wealth they produce, it\n\u25a0follows that somewhere in our distributing sys\ntem an unsound economic condition has develojied.\nSome of the wealth created by labor and the farm\ner is being unduly aund unsoundly absorbed by\nsome one else to the injury of a stable economic\ncondition.\nIt is of little avail to freeze wages and prices\nif somewhere else in the national economic sys\ntem others absorb that part of the national wealth\ncreated each year which should go to the primary\nproducers.\nThe worker most properly will defend his\nstandard of living which is based upon the real\nwage he receives, the purchasing power of the dol\nlars in his pay envelope. There can lie no national\nprosperity in any real sense unless the wage earn\ner\u2019s real wage is maintained, and for that matter\nincreased. Aside from maintaining the real wage,\nto permit a steady increase in prices, establishes\nan exceedingly dangerous condition to national\nwelfare.\nt--------------------------\u00bb-------------------------\nPROFITS WARRANT A RAISE IN WAGES\n\u201c13USINESS- i\u00ab in a very favorable profit position\ntoday, with excellent prospects for the period\nthat lies ahead. Throughout industry, and in\nevery branch of industry, profits have been and\nstill are very good indeed.\u201d\u2014President Truman.\nWhen President Truman referred to business\u2019\n\u201cfavorable profit position\u201d in his Oct. 30 speech,\nhe was basing it on a report handed to him the\nweek before by the Reconversion Advisory Board\nwhich showed that industry can afford to raise\nbasic wage rate at least 24' without increasing\nprices. 4\nThe government study found that industry\nwill save 10% of its gross earnings by repeal of\nthe excess profits tax, 9.5% by partial elimina\ntion of wartime incentive premiums and 4.5% by\nreduction of wartime overtime pay.\nEven with a 21% wage increase industry\u2019s\n'total wage bill would still be more than 20% below\nthat of last April\u2014and its profits would be more\nthan twice as high, after taxes, as before the war.\nSTRIKES AND RECONVERSION\nIT IS the established policy of the American Fed\neration of I^abor to negotiate wages and other\nconditions around the conference table and to use\nthe strike weapon only as a last resort. Thousands\nof AFL members have proved in the last few\nweeks that this method is effective and construc\u00ad\nThey are at work at higher wages today, and\ntheir plants are making speedy progress in recon\nversion.\nPresident Green of the A FL has urged the\nfell use of peaceful methods in the settlement of\ndisputes. In this connection the AFL monthly eco\nnomic survey points out:\n\u201cExtreme action at this time will arouse\npublic prejudice and harm labor\u2019s cause, and it cer\ntainly will delay reconversion and full production\non which we must depend for jobs.\u201d\n\u2018a1\nTHERE IS NO OTHER WAY\nTN FIVE OUT OF every six years, since the Civil\n1 War ended, we have suffered from sizable un\nemployment in our country. Unemployment and\ndepressions seemed to follow wars with monoto\nnous regularity. For a short time, after each war,\nwe experienced a temporary boom, followed by a\nroller-coaster drop in employment that took our\nbreath away.\nNow we are at the end of the most destruc\ntive war in all history. And unless we get together\nand plan firmly for continuous full employment,\nwe shall again be faced with a depression far\nworse than the one created by World War I.\nDepressions breed wars. But we can see clear\nly now that another World War might mean the\nend of civilized living.\nWe already have the atomic bomb which\ncan pulverize everything within several square\nmiles. The atomic bomb is not the only destruc\ntive weapon we have discovered or perfected dur\ning this war. There are the jet-propelled bombers\nthe robot bombs radar other precision instru\nments for detection of targets the deadlier ex\nplosives target-seeking bombs. To these we shall\nsurely add death-rays of invisible light and many\nother devices that are as yet in the realm of ex\nperiment.\nThis we know with cetrainty:\nEihter we build our future for peace or\nwe must face the prospect of another war within\nour lifetime\u2014a war in which mankind may perish.\nWe now know how near we came to complete\ndestruction in our war with Fascism. If Hitler and\nHirohito had obtained the atomic bomb before\nus, how much of the civilized world would they\nhave spared?\nFate and Providence spared us. But there is\nno guarantee that they will spare us again\u2014if we\nlet it happen again.\nIt is up to all of us to prevent another World\nWar.\nTo prevent war, we must prevent another de\npression.\nWe can prevent another depression only if\nwe nail down and secure continuous full employ\nment. We must use what it takes to prevent the\ncatastrophe of mass unemployment just as we\nneed our resources in cooperative endeavor to\nprevent the catastrophe of fascism from over\nwhelming our world.\u201d\nThere is no other way.\nWAR\u2019S COST-VICTORY LOAN\nVVE\u2019VE WON the war, or have we? To be sure,\nwe\u2019ve won the fighting. But, no, we haven\u2019t\nwon the war. Because in order to win the war\nwe must win the peace first. And just as long\nas there is an armless veteran without a new arm\nand trained for a job he can do, we haven\u2019t won\nthe peace.\nWe haven\u2019t been told such things as this too\nfrequently. But the war\u2019s cost and veteran assis\ntance will total about 434 billion dollars by next\nJune. That\u2019s a staggering sum, but freedom is\nwell worth that many times over. Some one must\npay this cost and that some one is all of us.\nThat is one of the reasons why our govern\nment planned the Victory Loan campaign for\n$11,000,000,000. That is why this mqney is needed\nto give hospitalization, training and opportunity\nto the men who sacrificed so muoh for us, so that\nwe could one day raise the roof when Japan sur\nrendered.\nSure we bought War Bonds. But that was\nto win the war. We didn\u2019t want to get licked and\noverrun by a horde of enemies. Not us. So we\nbought War Bonds. But now, now comes the test.\nWith no enemy available to overrun us if things\ngo wrong we must not become selfish.\nWe still have a job to do. Our boys are still\nin Europe and Japan and will continue to be there\na long time. They\u2019ll need clothes, food, the best\nof everything. That is another reason for the Vic\ntory Loan.\nFreedom\u2014even the winning of a war\u2014come\nhigh. But it\u2019s worth it.\nDo you agree?\nWHO MAKES OUR LAWS?\nIJILL, BOB and BEN hold good-standing mem\nbership cards in their local union. They are\nthe local union. Along with the Bills, Bobs and\nliens in all the other locals composing an inter\nnational organization, they are the international\nunion.\nBill attends every meeting, rain or shine,\nwhen big issues, little issues or no issues at all\nare to be voted on. He is steady. You can count\non him.\nBob is a swell fellow, too. He doesn\u2019t get\naround to the meeting hall regularly, but when\nanything of importance is up, he is there. You\ncan be sure of that.\nBen doesn\u2019t bother at all about attending\nmeetings. \u201cLet Bill and Bob take care of things\u201d\nis his motto. That is the way it works out, any\nway\u2014he thinks.\nBut Ben is wrong. The vote he did not cast\ncan mean a majority for or against an issue. His\nabsence from the local meeting can make all the\ndifference in the outcome of a total vote, let the\nissue be local or international.\nWho makes our\nWhy, Bill, and Ben.\n-----Bob\u2014laws?\nGOOD APPOINTMENT\nJTR. JOHN R. STEELMAN, former director of\nU the Conciliation Service, U. S. Department of\nLabor, has been named to the White House staff.\nIt is not yet clear just what his full duties will be\nbut broadly speaking, he will advise and assist the\nPresident and Administration with respect to\nlabor, industry and related economics meaning\nchiefly, labor relations.\nAppointment of Dr. Steelman is expected to\nlienefit not only the Administration but the gen\neral public. He understands labor relations prob\nably as well as any man in the country. He has the\nessential knowledge of labor and industry and\nof great importance, he commands the respect and\nconfidence of his fellowmen in all walks of life.\nDr. Steelman made a fine record as head of\nthe Conciliation Service and labor and industry\nwill be pleased that he has been given a further\nopportunity to render outstanding public service.\nTHE POTTERS HERALD\nof\ntOfi&Eg\nW\u00a9BW6*K\nLOWgR\ntak^-homc\nHIGHER PRICES\ntill\nn\u00bb\nhi\n\u2019I\n4- A\nis\nBy TRAVIS K. HEDRICK, Federated Press\nTURNING POINT FOR TRUMAN\nWashington (FP).\u2014Americans by the millions heard some of the funda\nmentals of economics in President Harry S. Truman\u2019s long awaited wage\nprice speech Oct. 30.\nAlthough many words were devoted to some simple truths most of us\nlearned in high school, they needed, saying because of the way they had been\ndistorted by spokesmen of big business.\nLabor with a big \u201cL\u201d has been played up as something especially dread\nful jand bad. Truman brought home the fact that a $20 billion cut in take\nhone pay is more than a delightful sock in the kisser to some horrible union\nmembers. He demonstrated that the corner butcher and drug store man\nwill-be hurt too\u2014and that the end of overtime pay could lead to wide un\nemployment.\nTruman avoided suggesting a definite percentage that wages should in\ncrease although it is an open secret that he has documented surveys show\ning that industry as a whole could grant at least 23% without hurting its\nprofits position.\nWhile labor doesn\u2019t like the failure to set out a program it can find\nlittle wrong with Truman\u2019s forthright setting otit the reasons why all in\ndustry can afford to grant imperative wage increases end of time and\nhalf, down grade of jobs, increased productivity of labor, and the very favor\nable profit position of business.\nTruman seems determined that the increases be granted, and left just\none major loophole for business to use as an escape route\u2014his six months\ntrial proposal.\nThis is a little device that those who wish to sabotage the program\nwill be sure not to miss.\nThis loophole offers business a chance to keep production low, unit\ncosts high, and come to the government six months hence with \u201cproof of its\nneed for upward price increases.\u201d\nThe danger in this game of sabotage comes not from the isolated instance\nwherein a manufacturer tries it, but in its wide adoption which can spread\nlike a prairie fire and drop the country into the pit of depression\nfore the six months are up.\nIf enough firms slow down production reconversion will remain\nand there will be more than the anticipated' 8 million Americans\nthe streets next spring.\nA more hopeful sign appears in the opening section of the\nspeech in which for the first time, he publicly takes off his gloves to slap at\nthe tories in Congress who are snarling up the reconversion plan of the ad\nministration.\nTruman has been long-suffering in his dealings with the House ways\nand means committee and that queer buhch of ducks comprising the House\ncommittee on executive department expenditures.\nApparently he has decided the honeymoon is over and he is ready to\nname names in order to bring pressure for enactment of the unemployment\ncompensation measure, /he full employment bill, and the retention of the\nU. S. Employment Service in federal control.\nWe can all hope this speech marks a turning point in Truman\u2019s career.\nHe stood up to the editorial warnings of the big papers that no wage in\ncreases are possible without price boosts. He replied business can pay out of\nprofits.\nPerhaps he deserves a small cheer\u2014while some of us watch the back\ndoor to the White House\u2014just in case.\nYOUR JOB AND THE LAW\nFOREMEN\u2019S UNIONS\nOne of the really hot questions in labor relations today is the subject\nforemen and their unions.\nAfter passage of the wage-hour law many employers avoided overtime\nprovisions of the law by reclassifying certain workers as foremen. These\nworkers were expected to put in more hours for less pay, and soon found\nthat the \u201chonor\u201d of being a foreman didn\u2019t mean much when payday rolled\naround. It was natural then, for these and other foremen to want to reap\nfor themselves some of the benefits they had seen the rank and file obtain\nthrough collective bargaining.\nThere\u2019s nothing in the Wagner act which forbids the organization of\nforemen into unions. As a matter of fact the NLRB has even ordered back\npay and reinstatement for foremen who were fired for engaging in legitimate\nunion activity.\nOne question that was left unsettled was whether foremen could belong\nto a union which included rank and file. That question is before the Labor\nBoard now in the mine foremen case. Foremen have always been members\nof unions which included rank and file in the printing, carpentry and maritime\ntrades and there the NLRB decided that it was proper. But it has decided\nthose cases because there was a history of doing things that way in\nthose trades. The miners case will determine if the foremen can belong to a\nrank and file union even where it was never done before that way.\nIndustry doesn\u2019t like the idea of foremen\u2019s unions. It reasons that if a\nforeman is a member of a union, any union, he\u2019ll cooperate with the rank and\nfile, and that this will result in \u201cdivided loyalty.\u201d\nThere are problems for the unions, too. For exampie, foremen might af\nfiliate w\u2019ith one rank and file international whereas the workers might be\nlong to another international.\nIf the foremen\u2019s International decided to do a little raiding, the foremen\nwould be in a position to put a lot of heat on the rank and file to change\ntheir affiliation.\nThe NLRB has already ruled that a foreman who uses his power to\nthreaten workers in the choice of their union loses any protection he has\nhad under the Wagner act and may be fired for this kind of illegal \u201cunion\nactivity.\u201d\nSome unionists fear th it it may become difficult to pin anti-union bias\non a boss who uses his unionized foremen to split a rank and file organization.\nBut the old rule still applies. The boss has not right to interfere, restrain or\nthreaten you in your free choice of a union.\nAnd if the foremen do this for the boss they are still his agents,\nwhether they are unionized or not. If a foreman \u201curges\u201d you to join a dif\nferent union let your union take it up with the boss. If he does nothing about\nit, its pretty clear that the foreman is only the boss\u2019s stooge and the NLRB\nwill have a pretty good idea as to whose side the boss is on.\nThus it becomes more important than ever for workers to write down any\nanti-union remarks, to make a note of anti-union acts, when, where and\nhow they occur. Remember. Write it down!\n4\nQUESTION:\u2014We have a company union in our shop. It was organized\nbefore the Wagner act was passed. Will the NLRB take a case against them\nafter all these years?\nANSWER:\u2014That all depends on what\u2019s happened. If your boss has in\nterfered in the running of the union, or has contributed financial or other\nsupport to it, its age will not protect it.\nNEW ROBES FOR HUNGER\nlong be-\na dream\nwalking\nTruman\nW. B. McKelvey, kilnman of Steubenville, was an East Liverpool visitor\nlast Saturday. Before removing to Steubenville five years ago, McKelvey\nwas employed at the Vodrey plant in East Liverpool. This week he began\nwork at new plant of the Steubenville pottery company north of the city.\nThe Franklin Pottery Co., operating a small plant at Lansdale, Pa., was\nrecently incorporated with a capital of $154,000.\nMiss Margaret Pope, sister of William Pope, superintendent of the Sum\nmitt China Company, Akron, Ohio, was the guest of East Liverpool friends\nover the week-end. She will visit with her sister, Mrs. Grace of Steubenville\nand her brother and his family in Akron, before returning to her home in\nNorth Carolina.\nThe next annual meeting of the American Ceramic Society will be held\nat Atlanta, Ga., the week of February 8-13, 1926. Already Atlantans are mak\ning extensive preparations for the entertainment of the visiting delegates and\ntheir wives and families. Governor Clifford Walker has been named honorary\nchairman of the reception committee.\nJosh Chadwick, Dave Cline and Ray Murray, jiggermen at plant No. 5\nof the Homer Laughlin China Co., Newell, W. Va., and Edward Chadwick, son\nof Josh\u2019s, spent several days of last week gunning for rabbits in the vicinity\nof Sisterville. Edward Chadwick acted as \u201cshofer\u201d for the party, the round\ntrip being made in his car.\nMore than 3,000 ham sandwiches wen* distributed by A. C. Boice Meat\nMarket last Saturday, in a demonstration of the delectable qualities of Sugar\ndale molasses cured hams. Of this number twenty were turned over to Na\ntional Secretary John D. McGillivray of the Brotherhood headquarters, for\ndivision among the employed staff.\nMrs. Daniel Cronin will be \u201ctoastmaster\u201d at the first annual banquet\nof the employees of the Standard Pottery Company, to be held on next Wed\nnesday evening in St. Stephen\u2019s Parish House, West Fourth street. Plates\nwill be laid for two hundred persons.\nThe Western Generalware Standing Committee met in session Monday\nevening. Evidence was given on several questions before the Committee. The\ncommittee gave consideration to this evidence but no settlements were made.\nFollowing an illness of thrw weeks from pneumonia, Anthony O\u2019Toole,\none of the best known potters and fraternal men in Trenton, died at St. Fran\ncis Hospital Wednesday. For many years he was secretary of Local Union No.\n35, N. B. of O. P., and financial secretary of Division No. 5, A. O. H.\nOn a plea of guilty for use of the mails to defraud, Joseph Crites, pro\nmoter of the O-Tex Oil Company, in which East Liverpool potters dropped\nconsiderable money, was fined $2,506 by Judge J. M. Killits in Toledo last\nweek, and sentenced to spend three years in the Federal prison at Atlanta, Ga.\nElbert Simms, jiggerman and Thurman Cunningham, decorator, have\nsevered their connections with the Hopewell China Corporation and returned\nto their homes in East Liverpool.\nCharles Hercules and George Esenhuth, will be the soloists and Judge\nS. W, Crawford the chief speaker at Local Union No. 95\u2019s notable banquet\nand social gathering next Tuesday evening at the Y. M. C. A. Other enter\ntainment numbers include a cello solo by Harry Waggoner and selections\nby Orr\u2019s Orchestra. President John T. Wood and Secretary John McGillivray\nhave been invited to attend.\nClayshop employees of plants No. 1 and 5 of the Homer Laughlin China\nCo., are loafing while a change is made to manufacture the new Ivory\nBody.\nUnemployment Insurance Information\nQ.\u2014Do I have to be 65 years or older to qualify for unemployment\ncompensation\nA.\u2014No\u2014you are confusing this insurance with old-age and survivors in\nsurance. Then} is no age limit for unemployment compensation. However, if\nyou are 65 years or older, you may wTant to file your claim for old-age bene\nfits. In some States the amount of old-age and survivors insurance for which\nyou are eligible is deducted from your unemployment compensation payments.\nIn other States you may collect both in the same period, in a few states you\nmust choose between these two types of benefits.\nQ.\u2014If I am 65 years old and can qualify for unemployment compen\nsation, can I also automatically qualify for old-age benefits?\nA.-\u2014No, the qualifications required are different. Sometimes you can\nqualify for both, sometimes for ony one type of insurance. Remember, there\nare two types of social insurance in this country today old-age and sur\nvivors insurance, which is a Federal system designed for fully insund work\ners who are 65 or over, and for their survivors if they die and unemploy\nment compensation, a Federal-State system, designed just for periods of\nunemployment.\nQ.\u2014If I am found eligible for unemployment benefits, will I automatically\nreceive benefits until I find a job?\nA.\u2014The process isn\u2019t automatic. You must report regularly each week\n(in some States every two weeks) to the United States employment office,\nregister for work, and notify the unemployment compensation office that\nou are still without a job.\nQ.\u2014What will happen if I don\u2019t report regularly\nA.\u2014If you miss your regular appointment without good cause, you will\nlose a week\u2019s benefits. It you are late for your appointment, but have good\ncause, your benefits may only be delayed.\nQ.\u2014What if I quit because I expect to be laid off soon anyway?\nA.\u2014That is not considered a good reason for quitting, and your benefits s\nwould be cancelled, reduced or postponed depending on your State law., -I\nThursday, November 8, 1945\nFrom The Herald Files\u2019\nTHIRTY-FIVE YEARS AGO\nLocal Union No. 9 at their meeting Friday evening issued three Transfer\ncards to members who are leaving the city and one was accepted from the\nKilndrawers, Local Union 17. Those who have left the city are Daniel Knowl\nson,\u2019who is now located at Crooksville. Timothy Murphy and John Carney,\nwho are working in Carrollton. John Cornell was the member received from\nNo. 17.\nWork is so plentiful at the H. R. Wyllie China company plant at Hunt\nington, W. Va., that the decorators are working four nights a week. Not only\nhas the fall trade been good, but the prospects are encouraging for a good\nbusiness throughout the winter, company officials stated.\nBrother Perry Day of Niles, Ohio, is wearing a smile that won\u2019t come\noff. He is married now. Got hitched up two weeks ago at Crooksville, Ohio.\nEdward Moore has resigned his sticking-up job at Niles and returned to\nhis home in East Liverpool.\nThe following is a report on the Standing Committee meeting held Ott\nOctober 24: The Portland coupe soup made by the K. T. K. Potteries com\npany, over which there has been a dispute as to price, was resubmitted by\nthe firm in a remodelled form. The alterations it was claimed brought it\nwithin the regular coupe size for which ten cents is paid.\nBrothers Thomas Hodge and Owens, representing kilnmens local No. 9,\nappeared before the committee, over sagger disputes, affecting the Warner\nKeffer China and Colonial Pottery companies. It was complained that the\nColonial had increased the number of 4ioles in its \u201ctea\u201d saggers from eight\nto nine in its \u201cfruits\u201d from eight to nine to ten holes and its five-inch, from\neight to ten holes all these changes have been made in the past three\nyears. Since the filing of the kilnmen\u2019s protest with the committee, other\nsagger changes it was charged had been made. The committee failed to\ncome to an agreement.\nThe Colonial six-inch plate made by the Limoges China company of\nSebring, was withdrawn from the committee at the request of Local Union\nNo. 44 of that city.\nA custard, from the Brookman pottery of Cincinnati, was settled at four\ncents per dozen.\nThe coupe soup and lug from the American China company at Toronto,\nO., was given some little c^isideration, but final action on it was deferred\nfor another week.\nA disoute over the size of certain jugs made at the Potters Co-operative\ncompany\u2019s plant, was brought before the committee by operatives in the\nemploy of the firm. The committee seemed to think that the matter was\ntaken care of by the general ware price list and referred the matter back to\nthe firm and to the men to settle among themselves.\nBrother James McCormick, jiggerman, presented a nappie grievance from\nthe Newell shop. He asked that the making price of the nappie be increased\nfrom 15 to 18 cents, claiming that he lost 18 cents in making the article\nthrough cracking. The extra price was allowed by the committee upon the\nunderstanding that if the loss can be reduced to five per cent, the former\nprice of 15 cents per dozen shall be restored.\nGreat Britain, with an army of 7,COO pottery workers, has been studying\nthe evils of the trade through a commission which has reported optimistically\nin a big volume to the effect that poisonous lead glazes are to be eliminated\nby more laws and closer inspections. \u201cPotters\u2019 rot,\u201d is the old, deadly ailment\nof the pottery worker. The name is colloquial, indicating the deterioration of\nthe lungs and the respiratory organs through inhalation of the fine, flinty\nparticals which come of the shaping and finishing of the pottery piece.\nThese particles, floating dry in the atmosphere, are drawn into the lungs\nand set up irritations, which are the beginning of the general breakdown of\nthe system, especially as the worker approaches middle life.\nTWENTY YEARS AGO\nEdward McDevitt, secretary of Local Union No. 99 of Clarksburg, W.\nVa., appeared before the Western Generalware Standing Committee at its\nmeeting in East Liverpool last Monday evening on a dipping question affect\ning the McNicol plant in Clarksburg.\nEmmett Green, jiggerman at the Bailey-Walker China Company\u2019s plant\nat Bedford, Ohio, attended the funeral of his brother-in-law, John Henry\nHeverly, more familiarly known as Harry in East Liverpool, Wednesday\nafternoon.\nV\nL,\n.-.4\nV","height":"26280","width":"20448"}}
